# 🚀 How to Create a GitHub Repository – Step by Step

## 🔧 Step 1: Log In to GitHub
- Visit [https://github.com](https://github.com)
- Log in using your GitHub credentials

---

## 📁 Step 2: Create a New Repository
1. On the top-right corner, click the ➕ **plus icon**
2. Select **"New repository"**
3. Or go directly to: [https://github.com/new](https://github.com/new)

---

## 📝 Step 3: Fill in Repository Details
- **Repository name**: e.g., `my-first-repo`
- **Description** *(optional)*: Short summary of your project
- **Visibility**:
  - `Public` – Anyone can see this repository
  - `Private` – Only you and collaborators can see it

### Optional settings:
- ✅ Check **"Add a README file"** to initialize your repo with a README
- ✅ Choose a `.gitignore` template (e.g., Python, Node, etc.)
- ✅ Select a license (e.g., MIT)

---

## ✅ Step 4: Click "Create repository"
- Your GitHub repository is now live and ready to use! 🎉

---

## 🧪 (Optional) Step 5: Clone the Repository Locally

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/your-repo-name.git
